column168: On June 4, 2023, at 1915 hours, personnel in the CSXT Walbridge, OH Yard discovered a strong odor emitting from CPCX 205191, a residue tank car of Combustible Liquid, N.O.S. The car was isolated and the shipper, Lubrizol, was notified via CHEMTREC (Report #2023-0605-00294).  EnviroServe, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the odor was emitting from a faulty Vacuum Relief Valve (VRV). The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper’s representative- Joe Eskra (440-364-9372, joe.eskra@lubrizol.com).  Contractor personnel removed the faulty VRV and secured the opening with a pipe plug.  The car was held at the CSX Walbridge yard pending a One Time Movement Approval (OTMA) from the FRA.

column168: SequenceEvent: The package was discovered at Mokena Station 610 on the 200 van line between work areas 216 and 236 by Alpimex BC, Andres Galvez, who immediately informed FedEx Ops Manager, Robert Sanner. During this time, it was discovered that two employees, Darrius Cozart and Jeremy Murray, had come in contact with the hazmat. Robert immediately instructed Darrius and Jeremy to rinse hands under water. Robert then placed damaged hazmat in bag + tote and promptly removed the package from the work area. He then communicated incident to ops admins, Emil Wisch (myself) and Keeli Palmateer.     Emil & Keeli instantly moved to location to assess the incident. There was a small amount of the hazmat spilled in drops under the line/rollers between work areas 216 and 236. There were two places where the spill was more concentrated (one was roughly an area of 10" X 2" and the other roughly 14" x 2"). Emil instructed nearby managers, package handlers, BCs and drivers to stay clear of the area and left to retrieve PPE and cleanup materials while Keeli researched first aid response for Darrius and Jeremy. She echoed Robert's instructions of running contact areas under water (adding the details running under COLD water for 15 MINUTES).    Darrius and Jeremy were moved to the office where Senior Manager, Nancy Morris and P&D Manager, Patryk Rojewski took over first aid.    Emil returned and spread AMPHOMAG neutralizer on spill locations while Keeli observed (training).    It was later discovered that the spill had actually originated in a trailer in the unload. It is unknown how the damage to the package occurred. There were no reports of any injuries to any employees who were near that trailer at the time the package was unloaded. Emil and Keeli moved to the location where the spill had originated. Emil spread AMPHOMAG neutralizer on all visible locations of the spilled hazmat while Keeli observed (training).    Emil and Keeli later returned to both locations where the neutralizer was spread and collected all materials in hazmat bags and totes.    There are no known complications to employees, Darrius Cozart or Jeremy Murray, proceeding the incident up to the time of this report. Both reported to work the following day with no known restrictions. DescribePack: There was a large hole/tear in the outer container of the package. Inside the package were 4 x 1 gallon plastic bottles of hazmat. Each bottle was contained in a plastic bag. One of those bottles' caps was unfastened. No damage DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: 1 hour is overestimating. I believe the release was less than 30 minutes (in our facility, station 610). Response was timely and well-coordinated. Mitigation included prompt first-aid to 2 affected employees, near-instant containment of damaged package allowing no future release and neutralization of acid to prevent any further damage to people, package and facility.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XAQ experienced a UN3264 Reaxis S 50 release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 100-gallons of product released to an 8' x 15' area of the trailer floor and to the asphalt lot below due to a pallet puncture. The product was transferred into a new tote. Soda ash and absorbents were utilized to clean the impacted areas along with other impacted freight. The damaged tote was then cut up and containerized. All waste was placed into (3) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: First Call Environmental was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 2.5ft-by-2.5ft area of the trailer floor and estimated that thirty (30) pounds of material was released due to a load shift  during  transit  damaging  one  (1)  poly  pail  causing  the  lid  to  come  off.  First  Call  Environmental personnel  moved all the  poly pails from the pallet to verify only  one (1)  pail was damaged and then swept up the released material. The non-damaged pails were restacked on to two pallets and shipped onto the consignee. The damaged poly pail was placed into one (1) 55-gallon metal drum along with the  recovered  released  material  and  was  staged  onsite  at  the  terminal  prior  to  the  contractor demobilizing.  The  generated  waste  will  remain  onsite  for  the  ESTES  DGRM  team  to  coordinate disposal.

column168: The 55 gallon drum in temporary storage at Veolia's PA 10-day intransit facility when it suddenly reacted, causing the drum to rupture. All of the contents of the drum release from the drum into secondary containment in the waste storage area.  While there were employees that were nearby when this occurred, there were no injuries and no exposures.  The pH of the liquid was tested and was found to be between 12 and 13.  This was the only drum in the shipment. Veolia contacted a third party emergency response company to clean up the spill and decontaminate the area.
column169: Veolia will verify with Johns Hopkins that they are classifying the hazardous waste properly. In the future, waste shipments from this generator will be shipped with vented bung caps in place. Shipments from this customer should not occur until a 24 hour waiting period has passed after a container has been filled and closed. Drums displaying any signs of pressure build up will be vented prior to transportation.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal NRG experienced a UN2924 Calfon AS 300 release from a 55-gallon metal drum. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 0.5-gallons of product released to a 40' x 1' area of the trailer floor onto the dock due to a forklift puncture. Absorbents were deployed and worked into the impacted areas. The damaged drum along with another dented drum of the same material were each placed into a 95-gallon poly overpack. All cleanup debris including the impacted pallet were placed into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

XPO Logistics terminal NNC experienced a release from 5 boxes, each containing (4) 1-gallon poly pails of UN1760 "Sparclean Detergent II". ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 2-quarts of product released to the pallet. The pallet was wiped down and neutralized. All damaged boxes and jugs of product were placed into (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
